# FTP

## 1️ FTP Basics Recap

- **Ports:** Control → 21, Data → 20
    
- **Modes:** Active (server connects back) / Passive (client initiates both)
    
- **Security:** Plaintext by default → sniffable; use FTPS/SFTP for encryption
    
- **Anonymous FTP:** Possible if `anonymous_enable=YES`
    

---

## 2️ vsFTPd Default Configuration

`sudo apt install vsftpd  # Check config cat /etc/vsftpd.conf | grep -v "#"  # Key settings listen=NO listen_ipv6=YES anonymous_enable=NO local_enable=YES write_enable=YES chroot_local_user=YES hide_ids=YES ls_recurse_enable=YES`

**Deny users:** `/etc/ftpusers`

`guest john kevin`

---

## 3 Enumerating FTP

`ftp <ip>             # Connect to FTP ls                   # List files ls -R                # Recursive directory listing get <file>           # Download file put <file>           # Upload file (if allowed) status               # Show connection status debug                # Debug info trace                # Packet trace`

**Recursive mirror with wget:**

`wget -m --no-passive ftp://anonymous:anonymous@<ip>`

---

## 4️ Nmap for FTP Enumeration

`sudo nmap -sV -p21 -sC -A 10.129.14.136 sudo nmap --script-updatedb sudo nmap -sV -p21 -sC -A 10.129.14.136 --script-trace`

**Useful NSE scripts:**

`ftp-anon.nse       # Check anonymous login ftp-syst.nse       # Server system info ftp-vsftpd-backdoor.nse ftp-brute.nse      # Brute-force credentials`

---

## 5️ Practical Exploitation Ideas

- Anonymous login → list/download files (`ls`, `get`)
    
- Writable directories → upload files (`put`) → possible reverse shell if synced with webserver
    
- Recursive listing → map directory structure (`ls -R`)
    
- SSL check → extract hostnames/email addresses
    

`openssl s_client -connect <ip>:21 -starttls ftp`

---

## 6️ Security Insights

- `hide_ids=YES` masks user IDs
    
- Writable anonymous directories are risky
    
- Fail2ban or similar tools mitigate brute-force attacks
    
- Recursive download gives full directory overview
    

